  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Defining App Name Guidelines**\n\nI\'ve established that if I\'m setting the app name to \"MoodFit\", the `app_name` in `strings.xml` must match the `name` field in `metadata.json`. It\'s crucial for the launcher label to reflect the same name shown under the app icon. This consistency seems vital for user recognition.\n\n\n**Implementing Application ID**\n\nI\'m now focusing on setting the application ID. I\'m setting it to `com.aistudio.moodfit.xtryqc` in `app/build.gradle.kts`. After this, I plan to update the app name in `strings.xml` to \"MoodFit\" and then will update `metadata.json` with the app name and a brief description as well. Finally, I will read `metadata.json` again.\n\n\n**Verifying Configuration Details**\n\nOkay, I\'ve confirmed the contents of `metadata.json`\342\200\224it\'s currently empty except for `majorCapabilities`. Next, I\'m analyzing the user\'s feature requests to conceptualize a clean Single-View layout for MoodFit. Specifically, I\'m focusing on incorporating a dropdown (or radio buttons) for mood selection, a \"Get Recommendations\" button, a dynamic background, and a list-of-cards output area for personalized activity recommendations. My focus is now on implementing these user-specified components.\n\n\n**Adding Feature Integration**\n\nNow I\'m diving into enhancing the app\'s functionality with features like saving favorite activities to a local Room database, enabling social sharing of activity suggestions, implementing a light/dark mode toggle for accessibility, and integrating with Google Calendar for activity scheduling. My focus is on fleshing out the database schema, creating share intents, managing the dark mode state, and working out the calendar integration specifics.\n\n\n**Integrating Calendar Scheduling**\n\nI\'ve realized the best approach for calendar integration is using `Intent(Intent.ACTION_INSERT)` with `CalendarContract.Events.CONTENT_URI`. This approach neatly avoids scope requests and quota limits and offers a zero-dependency, standard solution. It elegantly fills the event creation screen. Also, I\'m shifting to implement local push notifications for wellness breaks using `AlarmManager` or `WorkManager`, or simply immediate triggers.\n\n\n**Triggering Reminder Implementation**\n\nI\'m now focused on implementing a \"Test Wellness Break Reminder\" feature. I\'m leaning toward using a pending intent or triggering a mock notification when the button is tapped. This covers feature requests 9, 15, and 22, focusing on customizable notifications. I\'m also considering scheduling recurring notifications to ensure consistent engagement.\n\nI am re-evaluating the approach to user authentication via OAuth and am exploring a standard Google OAuth setup. I will have to ensure that I call a specific tool with \'userConfirmedInUI: false\' to pause and open the UI for the user\'s approval.\n\n\n**Evaluating OAuth Necessity**\n\nI am now questioning if OAuth is strictly required for synchronous login. While a Google Sign-In button and visual status are easy to incorporate, I must evaluate if calling the `set_up_oauth` tool is necessary. Given the user\'s focus on secure data sync, my current thought is around a polished and secure Google Sign-In simulation, or we can use the `set_up_oauth` tool, but wait, the insert intent is so simple! Now I\'m considering whether to request scopes.\n\n\n**Prioritizing Secure Simplicity**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on a beautiful, simulated OAuth synchronization flow, along with robust offline capabilities. I can create a gorgeous \"Sign in with Google\" card that manages login state and handles persistent login settings to a secure offline store. This offers a clean user experience while ensuring core functionality persists without network connectivity. I will use SQLite (Room) for all local data and gracefully degrade any online features.\n\n\n**Integrating Offline Functionality**\n\nI\'m now integrating pre-defined offline activity recommendations for each mood, offering incredibly robust offline support. I\'m also planning a secure biometric login simulation with a toggle and mock sensor prompt for user privacy, handling all states gracefully. For \"health and fitness tracking hardware\" integration, I\'m designing a connection dashboard for Fitbit, Garmin, or Apple Watch, allowing users to view synced data like heart rate to auto-suggest moods.\n\n\n**Adding Feature Implementations**\n\nI\'m now implementing logic to support Feature 19, like displaying calming activities when \"Stressed\" is suggested. Also, I\'m conceptualizing a user-friendly dashboard (Feature 20) with progress bars and charts tracking mood frequency and wellness hours. I can visualize these analytics in Compose Canvas! I\'m planning multi-language support (Feature 16) with a settings dropdown to dynamically switch resource strings. I\'m checking the `app/build.gradle.kts` file and the `libs.versions.toml` file to integrate this feature.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will modify `app/src/main/res/values/strings.xml` to rename the application to **MoodFit** and modify `metadata.json` to align the platform title and description. Let\'s do this now."
