  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Defining the Architecture**\n\nI\'m now focusing on defining the repository layer and ViewModel. My main concern is establishing how they\'ll manage state, interact with the Gemini API, handle potential errors, and gracefully manage offline scenarios. I\'m aiming for a robust and efficient architecture.\n\n\n**Designing the Repository**\n\nI\'m deep in the design of the `MoodFitRepository`. It will use `MoodFitDao` and `RetrofitClient`. I\'m creating functions to handle saved activities, favorites (using Room for persistence!), deletions, and Gemini API interactions. I\'ve designed the process for asking Gemini for recommendations based on mood, including fallback logic for offline scenarios using a pre-defined set, and graceful error handling. It\'s becoming quite robust.\n\n\n**Considering Configuration Options**\n\nI\'m now weighing the best approach for managing application configuration. I\'m exploring the use of `SharedPreferences`, `SQLite Room` or standard app configuration for storing the configurations. My plan is to implement the Gemini generation function within the `MoodFitRepository`, while ensuring the response is a clean JSON format for parsing. I\'m aiming for reliability with `org.json.JSONArray`. I\'ve added a few supporting classes.\n\n\n**Implementing Data Access**\n\nI\'ve implemented the data access functions within my `MoodFitDao`, focusing on asynchronous operations using `Dispatchers.IO` for database interactions. I\'ve designed and integrated functions for retrieving saved activities and mood logs as Flows, along with insertion, deletion, and checking for saved activities. I\'m ensuring robust error handling throughout.\n\n\n**Refining the API Interaction**\n\nI\'m now honing the Gemini API interaction within the repository. I\'ve built in a fallback mechanism for when the API key is absent or invalid, which ensures offline functionality. The request is constructed and includes health data as context, if available. I\'ve designed the prompts for the Gemini API call to return a structured JSON response.\n\n\n**Refining the JSON Generation**\n\nI\'m now focusing on refining the prompt for Gemini to ensure a clean JSON string array output. The output will include \"title,\" \"description,\" \"duration,\" \"type,\" and \"category\" fields. I\'m aiming for specific, actionable activity suggestions tailored to the mood. The prompt is designed to avoid markdown code block wrappers, and return ONLY a raw JSON string array. The intention is to streamline the parsing of the Gemini response.\n\n\n**Parsing the JSON Response**\n\nI\'m now fully immersed in parsing the JSON response from Gemini. I\'m focusing on the `cleanJsonString` function. I\'m extracting an array of `ActivitySuggestion` objects. I\'m handling potential `JSONException` scenarios during array or object creation. If everything goes well, I\'m returning a list of activity suggestions, otherwise, I\'m logging an error.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will create `MoodFitRepository.kt` which implements both the Live Gemini AI content generation (with smart JSON cleaning and native extraction) and the automatic offline fallback system. This provides bulletproof stability if network latency spikes or if the API key is unconfigured."
