  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Structuring the UI**\n\nI\'m now focusing on structuring the Jetpack Compose UI. I\'ve pinpointed key visible features, starting with a mood selector that includes a dropdown and radio buttons, and will design this incredibly well.\n\n\n**Designing the Mood Selector**\n\nI\'m now reimagining the mood selector. Instead of basic components, I envision beautiful horizontal Chips with icons (\342\230\200\357\270\217, \360\237\215\203, \360\237\214\231, \342\232\241, \342\230\225) alongside a dropdown or radio buttons for flexibility. The \"Get Recommendations\" button will feature dynamic animations and Material 3 layouts. Plus, the app\'s background will dynamically change, from pastel peach to soft purple, based on the selected mood, with corresponding dark mode color palettes.\n\n\n**Defining the Core Features**\n\nI\'m now diving into the output area design, which will showcase three personalized activities on beautiful Material 3 Cards. Each will include a title, description, duration, and type/category tags. I\'m focusing on the interactive buttons: Favorite (heart), Schedule (calendar), and Share (share icon), and how these will save to the Room database, or open an event creation screen, and allow the sharing of activities, respectively. I am giving a lot of thought to the Favorites section and Analytics components that will come after this.\n\n\n**Implementing New Features**\n\nI\'ve just added three core features: an OAuth authentication card for simulated Google account connections, a health device integration panel displaying simulated data with adaptive activity adjustments, and accessibility controls with light/dark mode, multilingual support, and a biometrics lock. I\'m focusing on the native Compose Canvas implementation, as well as testing the dynamic biometric prompt.\n\n\n**Implementing Notifications**\n\nI\'m now implementing the push notification feature, focusing on a reminder toggle with a custom rate setting using a slider or dropdown. I\'m prioritizing an interactive \"Test Break Alarm Notification\" button that triggers a system-level notification, mimicking a real push, fully runnable within the emulator preview. I\'ve switched gears to using standard helper code to create a notification channel and send an actual Android notice, and am constructing and displaying a live Android System Notification in Kotlin now!\n\n\n**Defining the Notification Logic**\n\nI\'m now integrating notification functionality, and have just defined the `sendLocalNotification` function in Kotlin. This function encapsulates the creation and display of system-level notifications. It includes channel setup, a safe built-in icon, and uses a standard notification builder. I\'ve designed it to auto-cancel after interaction, and have assigned priority default.\n\n\n**Integrating Material Icons**\n\nI\'ve just confirmed the availability of Jetpack Compose Material 3 icons like Favorite, Share, and DateRange, and a lot more! I\'m now looking at using these defaults instead of custom drawables to improve functionality and standard icons, starting with `Icons.Default.Clear`, and am considering expanding the options for expander or triangle icons using `Icon(imageVector = ...)` to avoid unresolved symbols.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will now inspect the project\'s Theme and Color definitions in `ui/theme` before writing our primary layout files. This ensures we integrate seamlessly with the exist theme wrapper."
