  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Designing the Core Layout**\n\nI\'m thinking about the structure of the `MainActivity.kt` file. To handle 22 features within a single view while maintaining good design, I\'m leaning toward a Tab-based layout (or a horizontal navigation view with active capsules) to encapsulate everything.\n\n\n**Defining the Tabs**\n\nI\'ve been defining the tabs for the layout. The \"Explore\" tab will feature a mood picker using elegant chips with icons, plus radio buttons and a dropdown for diverse preferences. There\'ll be a connected health status bar, a \"Get Recommendations\" section, and AI-generated activity cards with actionable details and options for favoriting, scheduling, and sharing. The \"Favorites\" tab will show saved activities with empty state tips, and the ability to remove each item from the list.\n\n\n**Refining Analytic Displays**\n\nI\'m now diving into the analytics section. I\'m focusing on the implementation of a long-term analytics dashboard. I plan to use a custom-drawn Mood Wave Canvas to visually represent mood and energy over time. The \"Stats\" recap will show total check-ins and favorited routines. There will also be a check-in history list for journals.\n\n\n**Integrating Biometrics & Layout**\n\nI\'m now integrating the biometric lock. I\'ll include a toggle for biometrics and a \"Lock App Now\" button for testing fingerprint authentication. Furthermore, I\'ve decided to write the entire layout directly within `MainActivity.kt`, aiming for a highly visual and functional design that perfectly answers all requirements. I\'m also including the `sendLocalNotification` function for easy notification integration, and I\'m currently figuring out the necessary imports for layout structures, components, colors, and icons.\n\n\n**Incorporating Key Icons**\n\nI\'ve been focusing on adding the necessary icons, including settings, checks, locks, refreshes, warnings, dropdown arrows, deletes, and check circles, ensuring the UI is visually rich. I\'ve also incorporated safe drawing insets using `enableEdgeToEdge()`. I\'ve added a Google Calendar helper to schedule events based on the recommendation, including the ability to set the title, description, duration, location, and the start and end times.\n\n\n**Refining Activity Integration**\n\nI\'m incredibly pleased with the elegant integration into Google Calendar, using a direct native link! It\'s super robust and requires minimal setup. The share feature is just as simple and elegant; it\'s perfect, really. Now I\'ll focus on the custom Canvas drawing for our analytics and the implementation of a smooth mood wave.\n\n\n**Visualizing the Data**\n\nI\'m now focusing on a `MoodHistoryChart` to visualize mood logs, I intend to use a custom `Canvas` element, to display mood data on a graph. I\'m exploring connected points or bezier curves to generate a smooth, polished visualization. I\'m taking the most recent logs for display.\n\n\n**Implementing the Mood Chart**\n\nI\'ve crafted a smooth `MoodHistoryChart` with a custom `Canvas`. It now visualizes mood logs on a dynamic graph. I\'m using connected points to generate a visually smooth and polished visualization. The logic includes spacing and point mapping, the mood wave feels great!\n\n\n**Designing the Mock Dialog**\n\nI\'ve just added a mock unlock dialog. It\'s a simple, centered alert displaying a lock icon and a message about biometric security. The dialog triggers the `unlockBiometrics` call to the ViewModel.\n\n\n**Simulating Biometric Unlock**\n\nI\'ve implemented a simulated biometric unlock within a mock overlay. Tapping \"Scan Fingerprint\" immediately unlocks the system, mirroring a successful biometric scan. I\'ve also verified the direct instantiation of the ViewModel, creating the Room Database and Repository in `onCreate` to ensure fast construction and clean app structure.\n\n\n**Implementing Dynamic UI**\n\nI\'m now integrating dynamic UI changes based on mood selection, specifically focusing on background color adjustments in Compose. I\'m exploring how best to leverage state management for this visual responsiveness. I\'ll test it out within `MainActivity.kt` and ensure the theme transition is smooth and instant.\n\n\n**Defining Mood-Based Colors**\n\nI\'m now implementing mood-based color schemes with corresponding gradients for light and dark modes. I\'m focusing on aesthetic harmony, and creating a set of vibrant and fitting colors for Happy, Stressed, Tired, Productive, and Bored moods. I will implement a responsive Brush.verticalGradient for each theme based on `viewModel.selectedMood.collectAsStateWithLifecycle()` to achieve a dynamic background color change.\n\n\n**Verifying UI Components**\n\nI\'m now in the process of thoroughly reviewing imports and dependencies to guarantee a clean build for `MainActivity.kt`. I\'m confirming package availability, like `com.example.ui.theme.MyApplicationTheme`, and compiling a comprehensive import list for the visual components. I\'m focusing on ensuring all necessary features are accessible and the code remains syntactically correct.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will overwrite `app/src/main/java/com/example/MainActivity.kt` with the entire visually polished UI layout of **MoodFit**, implementing all 22 components, local database Room actions, real native sharing/scheduling intents, language packs, analytical canvases, and simulated biometric overrides."
