focusing on preserving functionality while ensuring the \"Vibrant Palette\" aesthetic is implemented. I\'m aiming to keep the radio buttons while making them visually congruent with the design, potentially themed using `moodColorAccent`, ensuring we don\'t break the app\'s functionality. I\'ll need to check how other mood selection options are displayed.\n\n\n**Enhancing Mood Selection**\n\nI\'m now contemplating how to replicate the HTML\'s mood selection grid within the app\'s UI. My objective is to create interactive buttons mirroring the HTML\'s style, while ensuring that the current selection controls are still functional. The goal is a visual consistency of the `Feeling` buttons, to complement and potentially replace the existing radio button or dropdown style of mood selection. I\'ll need to maintain any existing functionality.\n\n\n**Preserving Functionality**\n\nI\'m now focusing on preserving all existing app functionality while implementing the new theme. I realize I shouldn\'t be replacing any HTML elements, but only modifying CSS and container layouts. I will now integrate the HTML mockup\'s mood selector styling. I\'ll focus on the specific colors for the Mood button containers, which are `#6750A4` when selected, and `White.copy(alpha = 0.6f)` when unselected in light mode, with coordinated text colors, and the background color of `#EADDFF`. Finally, I\'ll need to check the NavigationBar.\n\n\n**Checking Theme Initialization**\n\nI\'m now investigating theme initialization within `MyApplicationTheme` to ensure our \"Vibrant Palette\" is correctly loaded. I\'ve found we can define a custom color scheme with specific values for primary, secondary, tertiary, and background. I\'m focusing on overriding the standard Material 3 color overrides and checking for any `dynamicColor` interference. I\'m also considering dark mode color schemes.\n\n\n**Preventing Dynamic Color Overrides**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the dynamic color feature and its potential to overri